Custom Chatbot Project

I've chosen the Wikipedia page for the videogame Return to Monkey Island. This game was released in 2022, after the training dataset cut-off for the model gpt-3.5-turbo-instruct of September of 2022. I've also chosen NOT to use Wikipedia's API, but to scrape the page's HTML instead to try to replicate excersize the extracting information from non structured (or semi-structured in this case) data.

My implementation uses version ^1.14.3 of the OpenAI API, so the notebook may not work on Udacity's embedded workspaces.

In[1]:
try:
    from dotenv import load_dotenv
    load_dotenv()
except ImportError:
    print("\x1b[31mdotenv is not available in this workspace. Set openai.api_key manually.\x1b[0m")
In[2]:
import re

from os import environ
from textwrap import dedent

import bs4
import openai
import pandas as pd
import requests
import tiktoken

from IPython.display import display, Code, Markdown
from ipywidgets import interactive, fixed, widgets
from jinja2 import Template
from scipy.spatial.distance import cosine  # OpenAI no longer provides openai.embeddings_utils
In[3]:
client = openai.Client(
    api_key=environ.get("OPENAI_API_KEY")
)

Model configuration

In[4]:
COMPLETION_MODEL_NAME = "gpt-3.5-turbo-instruct"
EMBEDDING_MODEL_NAME = "text-embedding-ada-002"
TOKENIZER_ENCODING = "cl100k_base"
MAX_ANSWER_TOKENS = 150
MAX_ENCODED_PROMPT_LENGTH = 2048  # Half the context window size according to https://platform.openai.com/docs/models/gpt-3-5-turbo
In[5]:
tokenizer = tiktoken.get_encoding(TOKENIZER_ENCODING)

Data Wrangling

In[6]:
response = requests.get("https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Return_to_Monkey_Island")
response.raise_for_status()
In[7]:
doc = bs4.BeautifulSoup(response.content, "html.parser")
In[8]:
display(Code(doc.prettify(), language="html"))

         <p>
          <i>
           <b>
            Return to Monkey Island
           </b>
          </i>
          is a
          <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Point-and-click_adventure_game" title="Point-and-click adventure game">
           point-and-click adventure game
          </a>
          developed by
          <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Terrible_Toybox" title="Terrible Toybox">
           Terrible Toybox
          </a>
          and published by
          <a href="/wiki/Devolver_Digital" title="Devolver Digital">
           Devolver Digital
          </a>
          . The sixth
          <i>
           <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Monkey_Island_(series)" title="Monkey Island (series)">
            Monkey Island
           </a>
          </i>
          game, it was released for
          <a href="/wiki/MacOS" title="MacOS">
           macOS
          </a>
          ,
          <a href="/wiki/Nintendo_Switch" title="Nintendo Switch">
           Nintendo Switch
          </a>
          , and
          <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Windows" title="Windows">
           Windows
          </a>
          on September 19, 2022,
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ign-releasedate_1-0">
           <a href="#cite_note-ign-releasedate-1">
            [1]
           </a>
          </sup>
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-theverge-releasedate_2-0">
           <a href="#cite_note-theverge-releasedate-2">
            [2]
           </a>
          </sup>
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-eurogamer-releasedate_3-0">
           <a href="#cite_note-eurogamer-releasedate-3">
            [3]
           </a>
          </sup>
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-arstechnica-interview2_4-0">
           <a href="#cite_note-arstechnica-interview2-4">
            [4]
           </a>
          </sup>
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ign-switch_5-0">
           <a href="#cite_note-ign-switch-5">
            [5]
           </a>
          </sup>
          for
          <a href="/wiki/Linux" title="Linux">
           Linux
          </a>
          on October 26, 2022,
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-linux-releasedate_6-0">
           <a href="#cite_note-linux-releasedate-6">
            [6]
           </a>
          </sup>
          for
          <a href="/wiki/PlayStation_5" title="PlayStation 5">
           PlayStation 5
          </a>
          and
          <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Xbox_Series_X/S" title="Xbox Series X/S">
           Xbox Series X/S
          </a>
          on November 8, 2022,
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-7">
           <a href="#cite_note-7">
            [7]
           </a>
          </sup>
          and for
          <a href="/wiki/IOS" title="IOS">
           iOS
          </a>
          and
          <a href="/wiki/Android_(operating_system)" title="Android (operating system)">
           Android
          </a>
          on July 27, 2023. It was the first
          <i>
           Monkey Island
          </i>
          game by the series' creator,
          <a href="/wiki/Ron_Gilbert" title="Ron Gilbert">
           Ron Gilbert
          </a>
          , since
          <i>
           <a href="/wiki/Monkey_Island_2:_LeChuck%27s_Revenge" title="Monkey Island 2: LeChuck's Revenge">
            Monkey Island 2: LeChuck's Revenge
           </a>
          </i>
          (1991).
         </p>
         <p>
          Gilbert worked on the first two
          <i>
           Monkey Island
          </i>
          games before leaving the development company,
          <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/LucasArts" title="LucasArts">
           LucasArts
          </a>
          , in 1992. Further installments were developed by LucasArts and
          <a href="/wiki/Telltale_Games" title="Telltale Games">
           Telltale Games
          </a>
          without him. The
          <a href="/wiki/The_Walt_Disney_Company" title="The Walt Disney Company">
           Walt Disney Company
          </a>
          acquired the rights to
          <i>
           Monkey Island
          </i>
          when it purchased
          <a href="/wiki/Lucasfilm" title="Lucasfilm">
           Lucasfilm
          </a>
          in 2012; in 2019, Gilbert negotiated to create a new
          <i>
           Monkey Island
          </i>
          with the designer
          <a href="/wiki/Dave_Grossman_(game_developer)" title="Dave Grossman (game developer)">
           Dave Grossman
          </a>
          , who had worked on the first two games.
          <i>
           Return to Monkey Island
          </i>
          was announced in April 2022.
          <a href="/wiki/Dominic_Armato" title="Dominic Armato">
           Dominic Armato
          </a>
          reprised his role as the protagonist,
          <a href="/wiki/Guybrush_Threepwood" title="Guybrush Threepwood">
           Guybrush Threepwood
          </a>
          . The game received generally positive reviews.
         </p>
         <meta property="mw:PageProp/toc">
          <h2>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Gameplay">
            Gameplay
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=Return_to_Monkey_Island&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Gameplay">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h2>
          <p>
           <i>
            Return to Monkey Island
           </i>
           is a 2D
           <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Point-and-click_adventure_game" title="Point-and-click adventure game">
            point-and-click adventure game
           </a>
           . The objective is to move the story forward by solving narrative-based puzzles. This can be done by exploring locations, talking to
           <a href="/wiki/Non-player_character" title="Non-player character">
            non-player characters
           </a>
           to acquire information, collecting items and using them at the right time. The player controls the pirate
           <a href="/wiki/Guybrush_Threepwood" title="Guybrush Threepwood">
            Guybrush Threepwood
           </a>
           , who sails the seas and visits islands.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ign-interview_9-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-ign-interview-9">
             [9]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-theverge-interview_10-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-theverge-interview-10">
             [10]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-venturebeat-crowle_11-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-venturebeat-crowle-11">
             [11]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           The user interface is different from previous 2D
           <i>
            Monkey Island
           </i>
           games. Tooltips over
           <a href="/wiki/Screen_hotspot" title="Screen hotspot">
            screen hotspots
           </a>
           guide the player's actions: when the cursor is moved over an interactive zone of the scene, a brief phrase appears, suggesting what action Guybrush will take.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-eurogamer-mim2_12-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-eurogamer-mim2-12">
             [12]
            </a>
           </sup>
           The inventory uses a
           <a href="/wiki/Drag_and_drop" title="Drag and drop">
            drag and drop
           </a>
           interface to easily use and combine items
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-pcgamer-mim2_13-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-pcgamer-mim2-13">
             [13]
            </a>
           </sup>
           and the interface has been designed to work with
           <a href="/wiki/Game_controller" title="Game controller">
            controllers
           </a>
           or mice.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-theverge-interview_10-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-theverge-interview-10">
             [10]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-arstechnica-interview_14-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-arstechnica-interview-14">
             [14]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           The game includes a hint system designed to discourage players from looking for walkthroughs online and make sense "in the fantasy" of the game. The game also includes a simplified mode called "casual mode" for less experienced players.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-arstechnica-interview_14-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-arstechnica-interview-14">
             [14]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <h2>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Synopsis">
            Synopsis
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=Return_to_Monkey_Island&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Synopsis">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h2>
          <h3>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Setting_and_characters">
            Setting and characters
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=Return_to_Monkey_Island&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Setting and characters">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h3>
          <p>
           <i>
            Return to Monkey Island
           </i>
           takes place on fictional islands in the
           <a href="/wiki/Caribbean" title="Caribbean">
            Caribbean
           </a>
           around the
           <a href="/wiki/Golden_Age_of_Piracy" title="Golden Age of Piracy">
            Golden Age of Piracy
           </a>
           , as with previous games of the franchise.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-2">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
           The game features a
           <a href="/wiki/Frame_story" title="Frame story">
            frame story
           </a>
           that continues from the ending of
           <i>
            LeChuck's Revenge
           </i>
           , while the primary narrative is set after
           <i>
            <a href="/wiki/Tales_of_Monkey_Island" title="Tales of Monkey Island">
             Tales of Monkey Island
            </a>
           </i>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-15">
            <a href="#cite_note-15">
             [15]
            </a>
           </sup>
           and follows Guybrush's journey to finally find the secret of Monkey Island.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-cbr-trailer_16-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-cbr-trailer-16">
             [16]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-gamerant-lastgame_17-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-gamerant-lastgame-17">
             [17]
            </a>
           </sup>
           Along the way, Guybrush revisits iconic locations from the series, such as Mle Island (which is now under new management) and Monkey Island.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-3">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-eurogamer-mim2_12-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-eurogamer-mim2-12">
             [12]
            </a>
           </sup>
           He also lands on islands that have never been explored before in previous games, like the chilly "Brr Muda" and "Terror Island".
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-screenrant-characters_18-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-screenrant-characters-18">
             [18]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-cbr-trailer_16-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-cbr-trailer-16">
             [16]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           Several of the main characters of the series return for the game: the pirate Guybrush Threepwood (
           <a href="/wiki/Dominic_Armato" title="Dominic Armato">
            Dominic Armato
           </a>
           ), his wife
           <a href="/wiki/Elaine_Marley" title="Elaine Marley">
            Elaine Marley
           </a>
           (
           <a href="/wiki/Alexandra_Boyd" title="Alexandra Boyd">
            Alexandra Boyd
           </a>
           ) and his arch-enemy zombie pirate
           <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/LeChuck" title="LeChuck">
            LeChuck
           </a>
           (
           <a href="/wiki/Jess_Harnell" title="Jess Harnell">
            Jess Harnell
           </a>
           ).
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-credits_19-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-credits-19">
             [19]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-gilbert-harnell_20-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-gilbert-harnell-20">
             [20]
            </a>
           </sup>
           Other returning characters include Murray the Demonic Talking Skull (
           <a href="/wiki/Denny_Delk" title="Denny Delk">
            Denny Delk
           </a>
           ), mapmaker Wally B. Feed (
           <a href="/wiki/Neil_Ross" title="Neil Ross">
            Neil Ross
           </a>
           ), used ship salesman Stan S. Stanman (
           <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Gavin_Hammon" title="Gavin Hammon">
            Gavin Hammon
           </a>
           ), Mle governor and former swordmaster Carla (
           <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Leilani_Jones_(actress)" title="Leilani Jones (actress)">
            Leilani Jones Wilmore
           </a>
           ), and the mysterious Corina the Voodoo Lady (Wilmore).
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-credits_19-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-credits-19">
             [19]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-4">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ign-interview_9-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-ign-interview-9">
             [9]
            </a>
           </sup>
           New characters include Captains Madison (
           <a href="/wiki/Alix_Wilton_Regan" title="Alix Wilton Regan">
            Alix Wilton Regan
           </a>
           ), Lila (
           <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Annie_Q." title="Annie Q.">
            Annie Q.
           </a>
           ), and Trent (LeQuan Bennett), the three new Pirate Leaders competing with Guybrush and LeChuck to find the secret.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-credits_19-2">
            <a href="#cite_note-credits-19">
             [19]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <h3>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Plot">
            Plot
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=Return_to_Monkey_Island&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Plot">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h3>
          <p>
           Guybrush and Elaine's son Boybrush (Ava Hauser) is playing with his friend Chuckie (
           <a href="/wiki/Courtenay_Taylor" title="Courtenay Taylor">
            Courtenay Taylor
           </a>
           ) at an amusement park, re-enacting his father's adventures. At Boybrush's prompting, Guybrush decides to tell him the story of how he found the secret of Monkey Island.
          </p>
          <p>
           Having learned that LeChuck has obtained a map to the exact location of the secret, Guybrush travels to Mle Island in an attempt to gather a crew and ship to get there first, but the new Pirate Leaders Madison, Lila, and Trent refuse to back his venture. With his options limited, Guybrush obtains a magical eyepatch that disguises him as a zombie, allowing him to infiltrate LeChuck's crew before they shove off. Along the way, the potion used to guide the ship to Monkey Island is ruined, but Guybrush discovers the Pirate Leaders are also heading for Monkey Island and secretly completes their potion so LeChuck's ship can follow them. As they approach the Island, Guybrush takes LeChuck's map and replaces it with a fake, but accidentally removes his eyepatch and LeChuck throws Guybrush overboard.
          </p>
          <p>
           After washing up on Monkey Island, Guybrush follows the map but falls into a trap by the Pirate Leaders, who had intended it for LeChuck. As they have the real map but it is magically-encrypted, they agree to a truce to find the secret's location. With Guybrush's help, the map reveals the secret to be at the International House of Mojo on Mle Island. The Pirate Leaders betray Guybrush and throw him off a cliff before setting sail; LeChuck, realizing the deception, pursues them. Elaine arrives to help Guybrush, and they escape the island by rebuilding his old ship, the
           <i>
            Sea Monkey
           </i>
           . While at sea, LeChuck battles the Pirate Leaders before eventually agreeing to a truce to find the secret.
          </p>
          <p>
           Arriving at the International House of Mojo, Guybrush learns the secret is hidden inside a safe locked by five golden keys, which have been scattered. Following a series of clues, Guybrush travels the Caribbean to find each of the keys, frequently leaving a trail of destruction in his wake due to his single-minded obsession with the secret. In his absence, LeChuck and the Pirate Leaders attempt to use magic to open the safe instead, but they eventually turn on one another and LeChuck kills the Pirate Leaders. After obtaining the last key, Guybrush opens the safe, only to find a locked chest. LeChuck appears and steals the chest, taking it back to Monkey Island to perform the necessary ritual to open it and obtain the secret. Guybrush and Elaine follow, though Elaine repeatedly questions if the secret could live up to his expectations.
          </p>
          <p>
           Descending beneath Monkey Island, Guybrush follows the catacombs and opens a hidden door. He emerges in a theme park recreation of Melee Island, revealing it to be the true setting of all his adventures, with LeChuck and the others all being animatronics. Guybrush can open the chest containing the secret and find a novelty T-shirt inside. Boybrush finds this ending unsatisfying and questions its veracity, but Guybrush remains ambiguous in his answers. Elaine arrives and invites Guybrush to join her on a new adventure. The game offers multiple different post-credits scenes depending on the player's choices in the final sequence.
          </p>
          <h2>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Development">
            Development
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=Return_to_Monkey_Island&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Development">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h2>
          <h3>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Origin_and_production">
            Origin and production
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=Return_to_Monkey_Island&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Origin and production">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h3>
          <figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb">
           <a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:Ron_Gilbert,_July_2013.jpg">
            <img alt="A brown haired man in a green plaid shirt looks into the camera while sitting on a ladder step." class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="1428" data-file-width="1132" decoding="async" height="214" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/Ron_Gilbert%2C_July_2013.jpg/170px-Ron_Gilbert%2C_July_2013.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/Ron_Gilbert%2C_July_2013.jpg/255px-Ron_Gilbert%2C_July_2013.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/Ron_Gilbert%2C_July_2013.jpg/340px-Ron_Gilbert%2C_July_2013.jpg 2x" width="170"/>
           </a>
           <figcaption>
            <i>
             Monkey Island
            </i>
            creator
            <a href="/wiki/Ron_Gilbert" title="Ron Gilbert">
             Ron Gilbert
            </a>
            returned after 31 years to finish his vision of the overarching story after the events of
            <i>
             Monkey Island 2
            </i>
            .
           </figcaption>
          </figure>
          <p>
           <a href="/wiki/Ron_Gilbert" title="Ron Gilbert">
            Ron Gilbert
           </a>
           , the creator of the
           <i>
            <a href="/wiki/Monkey_Island" title="Monkey Island">
             Monkey Island
            </a>
           </i>
           series, worked on the first two
           <i>
            Monkey Island
           </i>
           games before leaving the development company,
           <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/LucasArts" title="LucasArts">
            LucasArts
           </a>
           , in 1992. He often dreamt of making a new
           <i>
            Monkey Island
           </i>
           game but did not own the
           <a href="/wiki/Intellectual_property" title="Intellectual property">
            intellectual property
           </a>
           rights.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-cnet-interview_21-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-cnet-interview-21">
             [21]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-engadget-announcement_22-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-engadget-announcement-22">
             [22]
            </a>
           </sup>
           Further
           <i>
            Monkey Island
           </i>
           games were developed without Gilbert by LucasArts and
           <a href="/wiki/Telltale_Games" title="Telltale Games">
            Telltale Games
           </a>
           .
          </p>
          <p>
           In 2012, the
           <a href="/wiki/The_Walt_Disney_Company" title="The Walt Disney Company">
            Walt Disney Company
           </a>
           acquired the rights to
           <i>
            Monkey Island
           </i>
           when it purchased
           <a href="/wiki/Lucasfilm" title="Lucasfilm">
            Lucasfilm
           </a>
           . At
           <a href="/wiki/PAX_(event)" title="PAX (event)">
            PAX
           </a>
           2019, Nigel Lowrie, founder of
           <a href="/wiki/Devolver_Digital" title="Devolver Digital">
            Devolver Digital
           </a>
           , mentioned to Gilbert that he knew John Drake, who was in charge of licensing at Disney. Drake wanted to approach Disney about a new
           <i>
            Monkey Island
           </i>
           game.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-arstechnica-interview_14-2">
            <a href="#cite_note-arstechnica-interview-14">
             [14]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-cnet-interview_21-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-cnet-interview-21">
             [21]
            </a>
           </sup>
           In December, Gilbert invited
           <a href="/wiki/Dave_Grossman_(game_developer)" title="Dave Grossman (game developer)">
            Dave Grossman
           </a>
           , who had worked on the first two
           <i>
            Monkey Island
           </i>
           games, to work on a new installment.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-5">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           Gilbert and Grossman met in
           <a href="/wiki/Seattle" title="Seattle">
            Seattle
           </a>
           in January 2020
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-venturebeat-interview_23-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-venturebeat-interview-23">
             [23]
            </a>
           </sup>
           to discuss ideas, and felt confident that they could create a good game.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-6">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
           Lowrie approached Drake to pitch the game and Disney was willing to talk about it.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-7">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
           Gilbert had "lengthy conversations" with Disney to make sure his team would have creative freedom, allowing him to "build the game I wanted to build".
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-arstechnica-interview_14-3">
            <a href="#cite_note-arstechnica-interview-14">
             [14]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           <i>
            Return to Monkey Island
           </i>
           was developed for two years in secrecy.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ign-interview_9-2">
            <a href="#cite_note-ign-interview-9">
             [9]
            </a>
           </sup>
           Gilbert said: "I did not tell anybody. If you were not actually working on this project, you didn't know about it. I didn't tell my best friend. I didn't tell my mother, I didn't tell my sister".
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-8">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ign-interview_9-3">
            <a href="#cite_note-ign-interview-9">
             [9]
            </a>
           </sup>
           The team
           <a href="/wiki/Remote_work" title="Remote work">
            worked remotely
           </a>
           during the
           <a href="/wiki/COVID-19_pandemic" title="COVID-19 pandemic">
            COVID-19 pandemic
           </a>
           . At its peak, the development team consisted of 25 people.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-theverge-interview_10-2">
            <a href="#cite_note-theverge-interview-10">
             [10]
            </a>
           </sup>
           Compared to
           <i>
            <a href="/wiki/Thimbleweed_Park" title="Thimbleweed Park">
             Thimbleweed Park
            </a>
           </i>
           (2017), Gilbert's previous commercial game, the team working on
           <i>
            Return to Monkey Island
           </i>
           was bigger mainly because there were more artists on staff, such as animators and a dedicated
           <a href="/wiki/Storyboard" title="Storyboard">
            storyboard
           </a>
           artist.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-9">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <h3>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Writing">
            Writing
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=Return_to_Monkey_Island&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Writing">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h3>
          <p>
           It was important to Gilbert that
           <i>
            Return to Monkey Island
           </i>
           begins after the ending of
           <i>
            Monkey Island 2
           </i>
           , which is a cliffhanger showing Guybrush as a child at an amusement park. Gilbert left LucasArts after completing
           <i>
            Monkey Island 2
           </i>
           . Though he said that the later games "did their best" to resolve it, he wanted to "tackle it head on".
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ign-interview_9-4">
            <a href="#cite_note-ign-interview-9">
             [9]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           Gilbert described the position of
           <i>
            Return to Monkey Island
           </i>
           in the series timeline as "amorphous".
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-10">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
           He and Grossman discussed if and how the game should embrace the events of the other games.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ign-interview_9-5">
            <a href="#cite_note-ign-interview-9">
             [9]
            </a>
           </sup>
           They attempted to follow the existing canon where possible, but would ignore elements if it prevented them from telling a good story.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-theverge-interview_10-3">
            <a href="#cite_note-theverge-interview-10">
             [10]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-cnet-interview_21-2">
            <a href="#cite_note-cnet-interview-21">
             [21]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ign-interview_9-6">
            <a href="#cite_note-ign-interview-9">
             [9]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-11">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
           Gilbert felt that some of the
           <i>
            Monkey Island
           </i>
           games had become too whimsical, and he wanted the new game to just be a pirate adventure, focusing on Guybrush sailing the seas and visiting islands.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ign-interview_9-7">
            <a href="#cite_note-ign-interview-9">
             [9]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-12">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           Unlike the extemporaneous approach to writing that Grossman had early in his career, he now did things in more stages, working from the top down. He began with planning the big aspects and then moved on to the smaller details. To do this, he did a thumbnail pass where he tried to go through and quickly scribble out the entire game. During this process jokes pop into his head, which he made note of. He believed that by taking this approach, it would preserve the freshness of humor without sacrificing the planning that was needed in guiding other aspects of the game, such as artwork and puzzle design.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-pcgamer-magazine_24-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-pcgamer-magazine-24">
             [24]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <h3>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Art">
            Art
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=Return_to_Monkey_Island&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Art">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h3>
          <p>
           The art style differs from previous
           <i>
            Monkey Island
           </i>
           games. The team considered using
           <a href="/wiki/Pixel_art" title="Pixel art">
            pixel art
           </a>
           , but did not want to make a "throwback" game.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-smh-interview_25-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-smh-interview-25">
             [25]
            </a>
           </sup>
           Gilbert said that they had a lot more freedom and flexibility to not make it a pixel art game.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-theverge-interview_10-4">
            <a href="#cite_note-theverge-interview-10">
             [10]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           Searching for an art director, Gilbert recalled a drawing of a stylized Guybrush sent to him by the artist Rex Crowle in 2007, and discovered that Crowle had been a designer on the game
           <i>
            <a href="/wiki/LittleBigPlanet" title="LittleBigPlanet">
             LittleBigPlanet
            </a>
           </i>
           and the art director of
           <a href="/wiki/Double_Fine" title="Double Fine">
            Double Fine
           </a>
           's
           <i>
            <a href="/wiki/Knights_and_Bikes" title="Knights and Bikes">
             Knights and Bikes
            </a>
           </i>
           . Gilbert hired Crowle to create an innovative style for
           <i>
            Return to Monkey Island
           </i>
           as the art director.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-13">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-rps-announcement_26-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-rps-announcement-26">
             [26]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           Crowle, who played
           <i>
            <a href="/wiki/The_Secret_of_Monkey_Island" title="The Secret of Monkey Island">
             The Secret of Monkey Island
            </a>
           </i>
           as a child, took inspiration from other
           <i>
            Monkey Island
           </i>
           games and other 1990s LucasArts games such as
           <i>
            <a href="/wiki/Day_of_the_Tentacle" title="Day of the Tentacle">
             Day of the Tentacle
            </a>
           </i>
           . For
           <i>
            Return to Monkey Island
           </i>
           he defined a style reminiscent of a
           <a href="/wiki/Picture_book" title="Picture book">
            picture book
           </a>
           or a
           <a href="/wiki/Pop-up_book" title="Pop-up book">
            pop-up book
           </a>
           because it matched well with the main topics of the game: "We've taken something from all of the games, while making something new and specifically tailored to the story that Ron Gilbert and Dave Grossman wanted to tell. An art style has to connect with the core themes of the game you're making, its not an interchangeable thing that you apply like a Photoshop filter, and for this adventure a picture-book style was the right fit".
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-venturebeat-crowle_11-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-venturebeat-crowle-11">
             [11]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-pcgamer-magazine_24-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-pcgamer-magazine-24">
             [24]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <h3>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Music_and_voice_acting">
            Music and voice acting
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=Return_to_Monkey_Island&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Music and voice acting">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h3>
          <p>
           Composers
           <a href="/wiki/Michael_Land" title="Michael Land">
            Michael Land
           </a>
           ,
           <a href="/wiki/Peter_McConnell" title="Peter McConnell">
            Peter McConnell
           </a>
           , and
           <a href="/wiki/Clint_Bajakian" title="Clint Bajakian">
            Clint Bajakian
           </a>
           , who already worked on previous installments of the
           <i>
            Monkey Island
           </i>
           franchise, were hired to compose the game soundtrack.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-polygon-announcement_27-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-polygon-announcement-27">
             [27]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-14">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
           In an interview with
           <i>
            <a href="/wiki/Adventure_Gamers" title="Adventure Gamers">
             Adventure Gamers
            </a>
           </i>
           , Dave Grossman pointed out how easy it was to work with musicians who already knew the franchise very well. Having them back for the sequel was beneficial because they were already familiar with what was expected of them. The rest of the team could simply sit back and watch them create, knowing that they would deliver quality work.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-15">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           <a href="/wiki/Dominic_Armato" title="Dominic Armato">
            Dominic Armato
           </a>
           , the voice actor for Guybrush Threepwood in the previous games, was signed on to reprise the role
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-theverge-announcement_28-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-theverge-announcement-28">
             [28]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-eurogamer-announcement_29-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-eurogamer-announcement-29">
             [29]
            </a>
           </sup>
           and was happy to accept the offer. Gilbert met with Armato to have a chat about an unspecified "new game" and the voice actor was baffled when he discovered that the game in question was a
           <i>
            Monkey Island
           </i>
           game: "We got together, we had coffee, and I think he was very interested in the new game, almost kind of wondering whether maybe he could have a voice part in it. And then I told him that it was the new
           <i>
            Monkey Island
           </i>
           , and he was just floored".
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-theverge-interview_10-5">
            <a href="#cite_note-theverge-interview-10">
             [10]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           <a href="/wiki/Alexandra_Boyd" title="Alexandra Boyd">
            Alexandra Boyd
           </a>
           and
           <a href="/wiki/Denny_Delk" title="Denny Delk">
            Denny Delk
           </a>
           returned to voice Elaine and Murray the Talking Skull.
           <a href="/wiki/Earl_Boen" title="Earl Boen">
            Earl Boen
           </a>
           , the original voice of LeChuck, had retired from acting in 2017 and gave the developers his blessing to recast the role.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-16">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ign-interview_9-8">
            <a href="#cite_note-ign-interview-9">
             [9]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <a href="/wiki/Jess_Harnell" title="Jess Harnell">
            Jess Harnell
           </a>
           provided the new voice.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-gilbert-harnell_20-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-gilbert-harnell-20">
             [20]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           <a href="/wiki/Neil_Druckmann" title="Neil Druckmann">
            Neil Druckmann
           </a>
           , co-president of
           <a href="/wiki/Naughty_Dog" title="Naughty Dog">
            Naughty Dog
           </a>
           , has a voice cameo in the game.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-30">
            <a href="#cite_note-30">
             [30]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <h3>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Technical_design">
            Technical design
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=Return_to_Monkey_Island&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Technical design">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h3>
          <p>
           The team spent time making
           <i>
            Return to Monkey Island
           </i>
           enjoyable with a controller without making the experience worse for players who use a
           <a href="/wiki/Computer_mouse" title="Computer mouse">
            mouse
           </a>
           , which point-and-click adventure games typically use. One of the goals was "not distracting or detracting from what the mouse play is".
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-theverge-interview_10-6">
            <a href="#cite_note-theverge-interview-10">
             [10]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           The user interface differs from the clickable verbs or the pop-up action menu of
           <i>
            <a href="/wiki/The_Curse_of_Monkey_Island" title="The Curse of Monkey Island">
             The Curse of Monkey Island
            </a>
           </i>
           (1997). When the cursor stops over a screen hotspot, a brief message of what Guybrush is thinking appears, suggesting the action he will take if the player clicks.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-eurogamer-mim2_12-2">
            <a href="#cite_note-eurogamer-mim2-12">
             [12]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           Gilbert revamped the
           <a href="/wiki/Game_engine" title="Game engine">
            game engine
           </a>
           he used for
           <i>
            Thimbleweed Park
           </i>
           . The development of his free game
           <i>
            Delores: A Thimbleweed Park Mini-Adventure
           </i>
           , released in May 2020, worked as a testbed for the new engine.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-adventuregamers-interview_8-17">
            <a href="#cite_note-adventuregamers-interview-8">
             [8]
            </a>
           </sup>
           The developers added the ability to do camera zooms, pans, and pulls to draw attention to specific elements, which would have been difficult in the early 1990s.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-theverge-interview_10-7">
            <a href="#cite_note-theverge-interview-10">
             [10]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <h3>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Marketing">
            Marketing
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=Return_to_Monkey_Island&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Marketing">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h3>
          <p>
           On
           <a href="/wiki/April_Fools%27_Day" title="April Fools' Day">
            April Fools' Day
           </a>
           2022, Gilbert announced on his blog that he was working on a
           <i>
            Monkey Island
           </i>
           game, surprising the industry.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-gamerant-bigdeal_31-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-gamerant-bigdeal-31">
             [31]
            </a>
           </sup>
           On April 4, Devolver Digital published a teaser video on their YouTube channel and opened the official website.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ign-interview_9-9">
            <a href="#cite_note-ign-interview-9">
             [9]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-pcgamer-announcement_32-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-pcgamer-announcement-32">
             [32]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-polygon-announcement_27-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-polygon-announcement-27">
             [27]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-arstechnica-announcement_33-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-arstechnica-announcement-33">
             [33]
            </a>
           </sup>
           The website was updated in June to show an example of the game's dialogue-based gameplay. Visitors could ask Stan, a regular character in the series, about the new game.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-polygon-trailer_34-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-polygon-trailer-34">
             [34]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-rps-trailer_35-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-rps-trailer-35">
             [35]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           The game was advertised on the official website as "the exciting conclusion of the Monkey Island series", which led to speculation as to whether it would be the final chapter in the series. This was refuted when the developers described it as marketing text not written by them.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ign-lastgame_36-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-ign-lastgame-36">
             [36]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-gamerant-lastgame_17-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-gamerant-lastgame-17">
             [17]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-eurogamer-lastgame_37-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-eurogamer-lastgame-37">
             [37]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-hc-gamescom_38-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-hc-gamescom-38">
             [38]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           Starting from July 11, Gilbert and Grossman shared on Twitter a video clip of the game every Monday, calling the initiative "Monkey Island Monday". The clips revealed new locations, new characters and how the dialogue system and part of the user interface looked like.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-eurogamer-mim_39-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-eurogamer-mim-39">
             [39]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-rps-mim_40-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-rps-mim-40">
             [40]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-pcgamer-mim_41-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-pcgamer-mim-41">
             [41]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-nintendolife-mim_42-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-nintendolife-mim-42">
             [42]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-eurogamer-mim2_12-3">
            <a href="#cite_note-eurogamer-mim2-12">
             [12]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           The game was released on September 19, 2022, which coincided with
           <a href="/wiki/International_Talk_Like_a_Pirate_Day" title="International Talk Like a Pirate Day">
            International Talk Like a Pirate Day
           </a>
           . Preorders were opened on
           <a href="/wiki/Steam_(service)" title="Steam (service)">
            Steam
           </a>
           and
           <a href="/wiki/Nintendo_eShop" title="Nintendo eShop">
            Nintendo eShop
           </a>
           . As a pre-order bonus, players would get an in-game horse armor item that stays in their inventory and has no function, a humorous reference to a
           <a href="/wiki/Development_of_The_Elder_Scrolls_IV:_Oblivion#Downloadable_content" title="Development of The Elder Scrolls IV: Oblivion">
            controversial downloadable content (DLC)
           </a>
           for
           <i>
            <a href="/wiki/The_Elder_Scrolls_IV:_Oblivion" title="The Elder Scrolls IV: Oblivion">
             The Elder Scrolls IV: Oblivion
            </a>
           </i>
           .
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-theverge-releasedate_2-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-theverge-releasedate-2">
             [2]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ign-releasedate_1-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-ign-releasedate-1">
             [1]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-venturebeat-releasedate_43-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-venturebeat-releasedate-43">
             [43]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-destructoid-releasedate_44-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-destructoid-releasedate-44">
             [44]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <h2>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Reception">
            Reception
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=Return_to_Monkey_Island&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Reception">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h2>
          <h3>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Pre-release">
            Pre-release
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=Return_to_Monkey_Island&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Pre-release">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h3>
          <p>
           In May 2022, after the first teaser video and a few screenshots of
           <i>
            Return to Monkey Island
           </i>
           were released, the art style drew criticism from fans online. Gilbert wrote a post on his blog explaining why the style was chosen and expressing his disappointment in the response.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-cbr-backlash_45-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-cbr-backlash-45">
             [45]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-svg-backlash_46-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-svg-backlash-46">
             [46]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-nintendolife-backlash_47-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-nintendolife-backlash-47">
             [47]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ign-backlash_48-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-ign-backlash-48">
             [48]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-vgc-backlash_49-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-vgc-backlash-49">
             [49]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           A gameplay trailer was released on June 28 as part of a
           <a href="/wiki/Nintendo_Direct" title="Nintendo Direct">
            Nintendo Direct
           </a>
           event. This reignited the backlash, leading some people to insult and harass Gilbert on social media and his blog. As a result, Gilbert disabled comments in the blog and said that he would not talk further about
           <i>
            Return to Monkey Island
           </i>
           .
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-teverge-harassment_50-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-teverge-harassment-50">
             [50]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-eurogamer-harassment_51-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-eurogamer-harassment-51">
             [51]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-rps-harassment_52-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-rps-harassment-52">
             [52]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-polygon-harassment_53-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-polygon-harassment-53">
             [53]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-gamerant-harassment_54-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-gamerant-harassment-54">
             [54]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-gilbert-rectification_57-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-gilbert-rectification-57">
             [a]
            </a>
           </sup>
           Several developers publicly criticized the user behavior and supported Gilbert and his team, including
           <a href="/wiki/Cory_Barlog" title="Cory Barlog">
            Cory Barlog
           </a>
           of
           <a href="/wiki/Santa_Monica_Studio" title="Santa Monica Studio">
            Santa Monica Studio
           </a>
           and
           <a href="/wiki/Neil_Druckmann" title="Neil Druckmann">
            Neil Druckmann
           </a>
           of
           <a href="/wiki/Naughty_Dog" title="Naughty Dog">
            Naughty Dog
           </a>
           .
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-58">
            <a href="#cite_note-58">
             [57]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <h3>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Critical_response">
            Critical response
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=Return_to_Monkey_Island&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Critical response">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h3>

                  <img alt="" class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="110" data-file-width="108" decoding="async" height="11" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/11px-Star_full.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/17px-Star_full.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/22px-Star_full.svg.png 2x" width="11"/>
                 </span>
                </span>
                <span typeof="mw:File">
                 <span>
                  <img alt="" class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="110" data-file-width="108" decoding="async" height="11" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/11px-Star_full.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/17px-Star_full.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/22px-Star_full.svg.png 2x" width="11"/>
                 </span>
                </span>
                <span typeof="mw:File">
                 <span>
                  <img alt="" class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="110" data-file-width="108" decoding="async" height="11" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/11px-Star_full.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/17px-Star_full.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/22px-Star_full.svg.png 2x" width="11"/>
                 </span>
                </span>
                <span typeof="mw:File">
                 <span>
                  <img alt="" class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="110" data-file-width="108" decoding="async" height="11" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/11px-Star_full.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/17px-Star_full.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/22px-Star_full.svg.png 2x" width="11"/>
                 </span>
                </span>
                <span typeof="mw:File">
                 <span>
                  <img alt="" class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="110" data-file-width="108" decoding="async" height="11" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Star_empty.svg/11px-Star_empty.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Star_empty.svg/17px-Star_empty.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Star_empty.svg/22px-Star_empty.svg.png 2x" width="11"/>
                 </span>
                </span>
               </span>
               <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-77">
                <a href="#cite_note-77">
                 [76]
                </a>
               </sup>
              </td>
             </tr>
            </tbody>
           </table>
          </div>
          <p>
           <i>
            Return to Monkey Island
           </i>
           received "generally favorable" reviews, according to
           <a href="/wiki/Review_aggregator" title="Review aggregator">
            review aggregator
           </a>
           <a href="/wiki/Metacritic" title="Metacritic">
            Metacritic
           </a>
           .
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-MCPC_59-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-MCPC-59">
             [58]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-MCXSXS_60-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-MCXSXS-60">
             [59]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-MCPS5_61-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-MCPS5-61">
             [60]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-MCNS_62-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-MCNS-62">
             [61]
            </a>
           </sup>
           The website Pixel Bandits' review of the title lauded the game's commitment to the series, saying that "
           <i>
            Return
           </i>
           really captures the spirit of the original games and delivers an outstanding 21st century point and click adventure".
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-:0_78-0">
            <a href="#cite_note-:0-78">
             [77]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           Pixel also makes specific reference to the highly-changed art style, saying that "I thought I was going to hate the new art style, but when you get in game it's actually very fluid and well crafted".
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-:0_78-1">
            <a href="#cite_note-:0-78">
             [77]
            </a>
           </sup>
           <a href="/wiki/Rock_Paper_Shotgun" title="Rock Paper Shotgun">
            Rock, Paper, Shotgun
           </a>
           described the visuals as "vibrant and lovely, capturing the spirit of the earlier games but in a storybook style that is extremely fitting for this new adventure".
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-79">
            <a href="#cite_note-79">
             [78]
            </a>
           </sup>
           While
           <a href="/wiki/Polygon_(website)" title="Polygon (website)">
            Polygon
           </a>
           mentions "The downright ugly polygonal visuals of
           <i>
            Escape
           </i>
           and
           <i>
            Tales of Monkey Island
           </i>
           have been replaced with a sort of
           <a href="/wiki/Henry_Selick" title="Henry Selick">
            Henry Selick
           </a>
           aesthetic, like a living map populated by hinged paper dolls".
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-80">
            <a href="#cite_note-80">
             [79]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <p>
           Some reviewers acknowledged the game had a reduced difficulty level but struck a well-maintained pacing.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-81">
            <a href="#cite_note-81">
             [80]
            </a>
           </sup>
           The drop of the nine-verb interaction grid, and instead going with the drag-and-drop system limits some opportunities for comedy, but contributes to a seamless gameplay experience.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-82">
            <a href="#cite_note-82">
             [81]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <h3>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Sales">
            Sales
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=Return_to_Monkey_Island&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Sales">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h3>
          <p>
           GameSensor noted that the initial month after the launch of the game on Steam saw
           <i>
            Return to Monkey Island
           </i>
           achieve sales figures of approximately $3 million. During this same period, the sales volumes of
           <i>
            Return
           </i>
           reached close to 100,000 units. Comparing the game's release to a previous game developed by Terrible Toybox,
           <i>
            <a href="/wiki/Thimbleweed_Park" title="Thimbleweed Park">
             Thimbleweed Park
            </a>
           </i>
           , reveals that
           <i>
            Return
           </i>
           's revenue within its first month surpassed
           <i>
            Thimbleweed Park'
           </i>
           s sales during a similar timeframe by almost sixfold; while the number of copies sold for
           <i>
            Return
           </i>
           exceeded that of the developer's previous game threefold.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-83">
            <a href="#cite_note-83">
             [82]
            </a>
           </sup>
           The remarkable sales performance of
           <i>
            Return
           </i>
           has established it as the fastest-selling game within the series.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-84">
            <a href="#cite_note-84">
             [83]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>

                Martnez, David (2 September 2022).
                <a class="external text" href="https://www.hobbyconsolas.com/reportajes/nuevos-datos-return-monkey-island-entrevista-leyendas-ron-gilbert-dave-grossman-rex-crowle-1116227" rel="nofollow">
                 "Return to Monkey Island en otras plataformas, posibles secuelas y ms en una entrevista con las leyendas Ron Gilbert, Dave Grossman y Rex Crowle"
                </a>
                [Return to Monkey Island on other platforms, possible sequels and more in an interview with legends Ron Gilbert, Dave Grossman and Rex Crowle].
                <i>
                 HobbyConsolas
                </i>
                (in Spanish).
                <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220903113706/https://www.hobbyconsolas.com/reportajes/nuevos-datos-return-monkey-island-entrevista-leyendas-ron-gilbert-dave-grossman-rex-crowle-1116227" rel="nofollow">
                 Archived
                </a>
                from the original on 3 September 2022
                <span class="reference-accessdate">
                 . Retrieved
                 <span class="nowrap">
                  3 September
                 </span>
                 2022
                </span>
                .  [
                <b>
                 HC:
                </b>
                Why announce it as the final chapter of the saga, as it appeared on the Steam page? Wouldn't you like to come back after Return to Monkey Island?
                <b>
                 Ron:
                </b>
                I don't know where that came from. But I think that Disney would have a problem if we said that this is going to be the last chapter of the series. We can't say there won't be another Monkey Island.
                <b>
                 Grossman:
                </b>
                It was a marketing text that we didn't write.]

Extract the text all the p (every paragraph without its header) elements from the div with id mw-content-text.

In[9]:
elements_text = [element.text for element in doc.select('div#mw-content-text p')]
elements_text[:5]
Out[9]:
["Return to Monkey Island is a point-and-click adventure game developed by Terrible Toybox and published by Devolver Digital. The sixth Monkey Island game, it was released for macOS, Nintendo Switch, and Windows on September 19, 2022,[1][2][3][4][5] for Linux on October 26, 2022,[6] for PlayStation 5 and Xbox Series X/S on November 8, 2022,[7] and for iOS and Android on July 27, 2023. It was the first Monkey Island game by the series' creator, Ron Gilbert, since Monkey Island 2: LeChuck's Revenge (1991).\n",
 'Gilbert worked on the first two Monkey Island games before leaving the development company, LucasArts, in 1992. Further installments were developed by LucasArts and Telltale Games without him. The Walt Disney Company acquired the rights to Monkey Island when it purchased Lucasfilm in 2012; in 2019, Gilbert negotiated to create a new Monkey Island with the designer Dave Grossman, who had worked on the first two games. Return to Monkey Island was announced in April 2022. Dominic Armato reprised his role as the protagonist, Guybrush Threepwood. The game received generally positive reviews.\n',
 'Return to Monkey Island is a 2D point-and-click adventure game. The objective is to move the story forward by solving narrative-based puzzles. This can be done by exploring locations, talking to non-player characters to acquire information, collecting items and using them at the right time. The player controls the pirate Guybrush Threepwood, who sails the seas and visits islands.[8][9][10][11]\n',
 "The user interface is different from previous 2D Monkey Island games. Tooltips over screen hotspots guide the player's actions: when the cursor is moved over an interactive zone of the scene, a brief phrase appears, suggesting what action Guybrush will take.[12] The inventory uses a drag and drop interface to easily use and combine items[13] and the interface has been designed to work with controllers or mice.[10][8][14]\n",
 'The game includes a hint system designed to discourage players from looking for walkthroughs online and make sense "in the fantasy" of the game. The game also includes a simplified mode called "casual mode" for less experienced players.[14]\n']

Clean up the text by stripping whitespaces at the edges, and remove references and edit links.

In[10]:
elements_text = list(map(lambda t: re.sub(r"\[.*\]", "", t).strip(), elements_text))
elements_text[:5]
Out[10]:
["Return to Monkey Island is a point-and-click adventure game developed by Terrible Toybox and published by Devolver Digital. It was the first Monkey Island game by the series' creator, Ron Gilbert, since Monkey Island 2: LeChuck's Revenge (1991).",
 'Gilbert worked on the first two Monkey Island games before leaving the development company, LucasArts, in 1992. Further installments were developed by LucasArts and Telltale Games without him. The Walt Disney Company acquired the rights to Monkey Island when it purchased Lucasfilm in 2012; in 2019, Gilbert negotiated to create a new Monkey Island with the designer Dave Grossman, who had worked on the first two games. Return to Monkey Island was announced in April 2022. Dominic Armato reprised his role as the protagonist, Guybrush Threepwood. The game received generally positive reviews.',
 'Return to Monkey Island is a 2D point-and-click adventure game. The objective is to move the story forward by solving narrative-based puzzles. This can be done by exploring locations, talking to non-player characters to acquire information, collecting items and using them at the right time. The player controls the pirate Guybrush Threepwood, who sails the seas and visits islands.',

Custom Query Completion

In[20]:
def get_question_embeddings(question: str, openai_client: openai.OpenAI) -> list[float]:
    """
    Generate embeddings for a given question
    """
    response = client.embeddings.create(
        input=question,
        model=EMBEDDING_MODEL_NAME
    )
    return response.data[0].embedding
In[21]:
def get_context_df(
    question: str,
    data_df: pd.DataFrame,
    openai_client: openai.OpenAI
) -> pd.DataFrame:
    """
    Generate a context dataframe sorted by the cosine distance
    between the data row embeddings and the question embeddings.
    """
    question_embeddings = get_question_embeddings(question, openai_client)

    context_df = data_df.copy()
    # Since openai.embedding_utils is no longer available as of the 1.0 release of the OpenAI API, I based my solution to computing
    # the cosine distances from the last release where the module was available at
    # https://github.com/openai/openai-python/blob/v0.28.1/openai/embeddings_utils.py
    context_df["distances"] = context_df["embeddings"].apply(lambda x: cosine(question_embeddings, x))
    context_df.sort_values("distances", ascending=True, inplace=True)

    # I'm adding the cummulative sum of the encoded length to make it easier to filter out the rows that won't fit
    # the prompt.
    context_df["encoded_len_cumsum"] = context_df["encoded_len"].cumsum()
    
    return context_df
In[22]:
def create_prompt(
    question: str,
    data_df: pd.DataFrame,
    openai_client: openai.OpenAI,
    max_number_of_tokens: int = MAX_ENCODED_PROMPT_LENGTH
) -> str:
    question_prompt = Template(dedent("""\
        Answer the question based on the context below, and if the question
        can't be answered based on the context, say "I don't know"
        
        Context: 
        
        {{ context|trim }}
        
        ---
        
        Q: {{ question|trim }}
        A:
        """))

    # Compute the context-less prompt size
    empty_prompt_len = len(tokenizer.encode(question_prompt.render(context="", question=question)))

    # Get the context dataframe which includes a encoded_len_cumsum of the SORTED rows, so we can
    # just filter out the rows that won't fit the rendered prompt template.
    context_df = get_context_df(question, data_df, openai_client)
    context_df = context_df[context_df["encoded_len_cumsum"] + empty_prompt_len < max_number_of_tokens]

    # Construct the actua context
    context = "\n\n".join(context_df["text"].values)

    # Render the prompt template and return
    return question_prompt.render(context=context, question=question)

Custom Performance Demonstration

Question 1

When was Return to Monkey Island released?

In[23]:
question_1 = "When was Return To Monkey Island released?"
In[24]:
response = client.completions.create(
    model=COMPLETION_MODEL_NAME,
    prompt=question_1,
    max_tokens=MAX_ANSWER_TOKENS
)
display(Markdown(f"`{response.choices[0].text.strip()}`"))

Return To Monkey Island was never officially released. It was a fan-made sequel to the Monkey Island series, and as such, does not have an official release date. It was created by a group of developers using the original game's engine and assets, and was made available for free download on various websites. The project was eventually abandoned and is no longer available.

In[25]:
response = client.completions.create(
    model=COMPLETION_MODEL_NAME,
    prompt=create_prompt(question_1, data_df, client),
    max_tokens=MAX_ANSWER_TOKENS
)
display(Markdown(f"`{response.choices[0].text.strip()}`"))

Return To Monkey Island was released for macOS, Nintendo Switch, and Windows on September 19, 2022, and for iOS and Android on July 27, 2023.

Question 2

What is the name of Guybrush Threepwood's son?

In[26]:
question_2 = "What is the name of Guybrush Threepwood's son?"

response = client.completions.create(

Guybrush Threepwood does not have a son. He is fictional character from the Monkey Island series of video games, and the player controls him throughout the games. He does not have any canonical children within the game's storyline.

Interactive session

In[29]:
def process_input(
    input_text: str,
    max_tokens: int,
    temperature: float,
    data_df: pd.DataFrame,
    openai_client: openai.OpenAI,
):
    response = client.completions.create(
        model=COMPLETION_MODEL_NAME,
        prompt=create_prompt(input_text, data_df, client),
        max_tokens=MAX_ANSWER_TOKENS,
        temperature=temperature
    )
    display(Markdown(f"`{response.choices[0].text.strip()}`"))

        temperature=widgets.FloatSlider(min=0.0, max=2.0, value=1.0),
        data_df=fixed(data_df),
        openai_client=fixed(client)
    )
)
